lures.","test_description":"Call the real LLM API with structured test data containing specific metrics, numbers, and domain details. Generate summaries. Evaluate the output using automated checks (e.g., presence of all key metrics, verification that numerical values match input data, checking for obvious hallucinations) and/or human review. Run the test multiple times with the same input to catch non-deterministic failures. Include edge cases: missing optional fields, very large numbers, conflicting or ambiguous data.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Agentic-level testing with the real LLM is necessary because LLM accuracy is inherently non-deterministic and cannot be verified through mocks. Mocking would hide hallucinations, data omissions, and subtle misrepresentations that occur in real LLM behavior.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This end-to-end behavior requires testing real email delivery (SMTP server, authentication, email formatting, recipient parsing). While intermediate steps (data collection, summary generation) might use test doubles, the final delivery step requires real SMTP infrastructure. A unit or integration test with mocked email delivery would hide real failures like SMTP authentication issues, email format rejection by mail servers, TLS/encryption problems, or recipient address parsing bugs. System-level testing with a real or test SMTP server is the minimum to catch these delivery failures.","test_description":"Set up a test SMTP server (e.g., MailHog, local Postfix, or AWS SES test mode). Configure the script to deliver to the test server. Run the complete pipeline: collect data (using real or test doubles), generate summary (with real LLM or a production-like mock), format email with full headers, and send via SMTP. Verify that: (1) email is received by the test SMTP server, (2) email content and structure are correct, (3) recipient address is correctly formatted, (4) email headers are valid, (5) the message can be parsed by a mail client library.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"System-level testing with a test SMTP server is necessary to verify real email delivery behavior. Integration tests with a mocked SMTP client would miss format issues, authentication failures, and protocol-level problems.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior requires testing both real email service unavailability and the retry mechanism across scheduler boundaries. A unit test with a mocked SMTP client never tests unavailability scenarios. An integration test can verify file persistence logic but would miss real failures in the scheduler's retry orchestration, state persistence between runs, or timing issues. A system-level test with an actually unreachable SMTP server is needed to verify the complete pipeline: detect unavailability, save report to file, and ensure the scheduled retry actually triggers, reads the saved state, and succeeds on the next run.","test_description":"Set up a test SMTP server that is initially offline/unresponsive. Run the script's data collection and email delivery. Verify that: (1) SMTP connection fails, (2) the report is saved to a configured file path with recoverable state (metadata, original input), (3) the script logs retry intent. Bring the SMTP server online. Manually trigger the next scheduled run. Verify that: (4) the retry mechanism reads the saved report, (5) sends it via email successfully, (6) deletes or archives the temporary file, (7) logs success.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"System-level testing is necessary to verify both the actual file-save error path and the scheduler's retry mechanism working together. Integration tests would miss scheduler-level retry failures, and unit tests would not test real SMTP unavailability scenarios.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13456,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13456},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a16c09bd-52ea-4caf-b628-53ad2649ad03","uuid":"6a229e74-a873-4acf-a9c4-2a4fa31363e9"}
